english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of Shinbok Seon Temple in Gwangju, Greater Yuan and Goryeo
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Park, the commissioner of civil craftsmen, came to me and said: "In my youth I left my parents and entered service at the imperial court. Since the time of Emperor Wuzong, I have received abundant favor. When Emperor Renzong ascended the throne, I was treated with exceptional kindness as a former attendant of the Eastern Palace. How could I have thought of my homeland or yearned for my parents during those days? Later, by imperial command, I returned home by official transport. When I went to visit my native place, my father was already aged. He touched my back and said, 'Day and night I prayed for your prosperity and awaited your return. Now you have come.' He then took me to Shinbok Temple and said, 'This is where you played in your youth, when it lay overgrown with weeds. I gave everything our family possessed—even our clothing and caps—to pray for the king's blessing above and for your good fortune below. Now see how it has become a great temple.' Nearly twenty years have passed since then, yet his words ring in my ears still. I dare not forget them for a single day.

    Alas, not only did he give me life and nurture me, but he did not merely pray in his heart—he beseeched the Buddha himself. Thus do I understand that parental love for their children knows no bounds. How rare are those who repay such devotion with a child's own heart! Now my father has passed away, and I too grow old, yet I have not recorded the restoration of Shinbok Temple. This is my great negligence as a son. I shall obtain stone from Yeonsan and inscribe upon it a complete account, together with my father's own words and the names of my kinfolk, that I may place it in the temple courtyard for future generations to know that such was the love between my father and me, rooted in Heaven's own nature.

    You must write this for me." When I heard these words, I could not help but be moved. Among those who rush after wealth and position, wandering ten thousand miles from home in service, how many truly remember their native place and honor their parents? Consider our own people—many have risen to high station in the imperial palace and shone brilliantly for a time. Can we be certain that none have come to regard their homeland as foreign soil and treat their kinfolk as mere strangers? Yet Park, upon hearing once his father's words, held filial devotion in his heart throughout his life, and determined to have them carved in stone to endure forever. Could I refuse to record such a tale?

    The temple stands in Gwangju. Its founding coincided with the establishment of the district itself, though it has known times of decline and restoration. Now it possesses a hall for the Buddha, dwellings for the monks, deep galleries and covered walks, and an open courtyard and gates. It occupies the finest location in the district and has become a haven for contemplative monks of all regions. The work began in the Yuan-you era in the year jiazi and was completed in the final years of the Zhizhi era. The monk Yongqiu oversaw the project. Lacking permanent endowment, it was sustained by Park's gift of fifteen plots of excellent land in Bird Mountain west of the district town, and by his wife, née Kim, who contributed five hundred strings of paper currency for the temple's provisions.

    Gwangju held first rank among the districts of the Three Hans, and the Park clan was the great family of that district. From Park's grandfather Suudo onward, all served in the district's administration and were elders of the region. His father, named Gyeon, served as Lieutenant-Colonel and, upon advanced age, retired with the rank of Attendant of the Bureau of Gate Guards. He lived seventy-eight years and passed away at home on the second day of the ninth month in the year jiazi of the Taiding era, posthumously granted the rank of Senior Guard of the Court of Intimate Counselors. His mother, née Zhang, was enfeoffed as Lady of Tangzhen and died on the twenty-fifth day of the first month in the year yihai of the Yuantong era at age eighty-four.

    Park had two elder brothers and two younger brothers. The eldest, Hyo-jin, held the rank of Assistant General. The next, Ryeon, was a Major. The younger, Cheon-u, did not enter service. The last, Gwan, was governor of Ansan. His sister married Li Ju, Keeper of the Imperial Cellars. Hyo-jin had three sons and four daughters; his eldest son was Sun, the next was Miyalsilrye, now serving as Guard at the capital with the rank of Attendant of the Bureau of Gate Guards, and the third was Taljeobmokah. His daughters all married worthy men. Cheon-u had three sons named In-man, Pyeong, and Mun-bo. Gwan's three daughters all married worthy men. As for grandsons, granddaughters, and their spouses, they are numerous and not recorded here.

    Park's childhood name was Sarooltae. In the early years of Emperor Wuzong's reign, he entered palace service as an attendant by imperial command. The emperor always called him "Little Sarooltae" and subsequently granted this as his name. He was first appointed Director of the Imperial Equipage Bureau, then promoted to Counselor-at-Law and Commissioner of All Categories of Civil and Military Craftsmen for the Northern Region of the Great Capital. Of steadfast and careful nature, he enjoyed the favor of successive emperors, yet in time he withdrew humbly and spent his later years in Buddhist practice.
